00:16:05,240 --> 00:16:11,000
very aggressively for a product that did not 
change that fast before it had reached good  

187
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:15,960
product market fit already, hundreds of thousands 
of users on a daily basis, and all of a sudden  

188
00:16:15,960 --> 00:16:22,080
that you get a lot of people who want to make 
changes to it, to compete against this new threat.  

189
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:28,920
The platform is not so ready for so many people 
to work on it. And so we got to the inevitable,  

190
00:16:29,560 --> 00:16:33,720
okay, it's too much tech, we can't do 
much about it so we made the decision  

191
00:16:33,720 --> 00:16:38,720
to rewrite it. There's lots of literature 
around there around should you do rewrite?  

192
00:16:38,720 --> 00:16:42,840
Should you not do rewrite? You ask 
me now, I tell you never. Trust me.

193
00:16:42,840 --> 00:16:46,280
That's what most of the advice is, never 
do a rewrite, and people still do it.

194
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:52,280
Never do a rewrite, and there's good reasons for 
that. But basically we did that and out of it came  

195
00:16:52,280 --> 00:16:59,360
up actually a new product called Stride, which 
was initially "HipChat next gen." The problem is  

196
00:16:59,360 --> 00:17:05,000
that the product was great, but by the time 
we were done, Slack was just miles ahead of  

197
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:11,840
us. At that point, Microsoft launched Teams. 
I don't know if you remember this moment where  

198
00:17:11,840 --> 00:17:16,800
Slack put an ad in the, I think it was The New 
York Times, copying the Apple versus Microsoft  

199
00:17:16,800 --> 00:17:23,800
thing from ages before going, "Welcome to the 
game, welcome to the party, we'll welcome you  

200
00:17:23,800 --> 00:17:29,040
competitors," and stuff like that and Slack got 
pretty much destroyed by Teams. We started coming  

201
00:17:29,040 --> 00:17:32,640
because it was like Microsoft distribution 
advantage. Everyone in Office is going to  

202
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:38,480
get it. They're giving it for free as part of 
Office, it was unbundled I think a few months ago.

203
00:17:38,480 --> 00:17:43,360
Which is ironic because in theory, 
Atlassian also has that same advantage,  

204
00:17:43,360 --> 00:17:46,600
right? You have all these 
products, you could bundle it.

205
00:17:46,600 --> 00:17:48,948
We are going to talk about 
that actually in a minute.

206
00:17:48,948 --> 00:17:48,960
Okay, great.

207
00:17:48,960 --> 00:17:58,840
Because that was what helped us, how we thought 
we would win, and it was how I think we lost.

208
00:17:59,760 --> 00:18:00,800
Amazing. Let's get in.

209
00:18:00,800 --> 00:18:05,840
So anyway, this all happened, and in the end 
we executed the market. We sold HipChat and  

210
00:18:05,840 --> 00:18:10,440
Stride to Slack and basically exited 
the enterprise communications market.

211
00:18:10,440 --> 00:18:15,640
Just to double down that, but you sold 
that to Slack and now Salesforce basically,  

212
00:18:15,640 --> 00:18:19,560
that's the word ended. I don't 
know if people know that.

213
00:18:19,560 --> 00:18:27,520
Yeah, actually, it was noticed by the market in 
that as soon as we did that, our stock price went  

214
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:37,680
up. I think it was $60 back then and it went 
up to 70. I mean, that really sucked for us,  

215
00:18:37,680 --> 00:18:44,600
the team working on it. First, no one tells you, 
but failure, everyone tells you failure is great  

216
00:18:44,600 --> 00:18:50,240
because you learn so many things, but failure 
to start with really sucks. None of us here were  

217
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:57,160
really happy about this on the team because we 
had spent years, on my part, it was three years,  

218
00:18:57,160 --> 00:19:01,920
but the people who were before that on HipChat 
was longer than that. Obsessing over it,  

219
00:19:01,920 --> 00:19:06,120
obsessing over every detail, every customer 
conversation, every solution, should we rewrite,  

220
00:19:06,120 --> 00:19:10,560
should we this, should we do that?
So many intense conversations,  

221
00:19:10,560 --> 00:19:17,520
and from one day to the next, it didn't matter 
anymore. We had worked on something and that's it,  

222
00:19:17,520 --> 00:19:21,520
that's the end. I'm sure many startups have been 
through that before. For me it was the first time  

223
00:19:21,520 --> 00:19:25,960
it felt that personal, and the market the next 
day went, "Oh, you're stopping doing what you're  

224
00:19:25,960 --> 00:19:33,000
doing? Awesome. Yes, 10 more dollars to your 
stock price." So yeah, there's a personal side to  

225
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:38,360
all the stories. For us, there was a bit like the 
seven stages of grief after we shut down HipChat.

226
00:19:38,360 --> 00:19:42,280
How long was that period of mourning 
and stages for you and the team?

227
00:19:42,280 --> 00:19:49,600
It lasted a few months. I was not part of the 
decision making team for shutting down HipChat.  

228
00:19:49,600 --> 00:19:54,920
I was one of the product managers on the team 
leading one of the three pillars. I got brought  

229
00:19:54,920 --> 00:20:00,120
in, I think it was a month or two, a month 
before it was announced for the team to go,  

230
00:20:00,120 --> 00:20:06,120
"Hey, Tanguy, by the way, just so you know, 
HipChat is no more, and now your mission is  

231
00:20:06,120 --> 00:20:14,360
to find a new mission for the team after that."
We basically spend the next two, three months  

232
00:20:14,360 --> 00:20:19,600
trying to make sure that the squads were created 
to fully own what they do there, to make sure that  

233
00:20:19,600 --> 00:20:24,240
they're the ones talking to the customers, they're 
the other ones trying to come up with strategies,  

234
00:20:24,240 --> 00:20:29,280
trying to come up with solutions and everything 
in that area. As long as it was people interacting  

235
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:36,120
with Atlassian products on other surfaces, 
everything was fair game, and so there was a  

236
00:20:36,120 --> 00:20:41,120
lot of ups and downs and everything. I think it 
took about two, three months before we got back  

237
00:20:41,120 --> 00:20:49,000
to a new rhythm. And some people, when we talk 
about it, were still scarred by it basically.

238
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:51,800
What are some lessons from that experience?

239
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:58,160
Yeah, so the main one that I personally got from 
this, and it's back to the hypothesis that you  

240
00:20:58,160 --> 00:21:03,720
talked about, which we have all these successful 
products, we can expand into this one which is,  

241
00:21:03,720 --> 00:21:09,760
and I quote it, but it's just myself, don't 
eat your own bullshit, which is a mix of two  

242
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:16,400
things. We've got a company value that says 
open company, no bullshit. So we need to be  

243
00:21:16,400 --> 00:21:22,000
able to talk about the things like they are, and 
we don't try to make things sound smarter than  

244
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:26,000
they are. We don't try to hide the truth, we 
go after that truth, and we don't hide stuff  

245
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:30,920
from each other. We share with everyone, we are 
open by default. So that's one of the values and  

246
00:21:30,920 --> 00:21:36,920
we do a lot of dogfooding, so eat your own 
dog food. We do test our own software a lot. 

247
00:21:36,920 --> 00:21:44,120
I've noticed that sometimes there are things that 
we do while we tend to believe stuff because it's  

248
00:21:44,120 --> 00:21:51,320
worked for us before, and we have this assumption 
that it's going to keep working for us forever.  

249
00:21:51,320 --> 00:21:56,720
The founders keep telling us what took us here 
won't take us there. That's a thing we keep  

250
00:21:56,720 --> 00:22:01,920
hearing over and over again. But it's very easy 
for teams when they see success of something to  

251
00:22:01,920 --> 00:22:11,920
think that it's successful because of X, but X 
is not validated. That's where we go back to the  

252
00:22:11,920 --> 00:22:18,480
topic we've got today, which is why is doing this 
in a successful company harder sometimes. Well,  

253
00:22:18,480 --> 00:22:26,040
Atlassian was successful with the playbook, and 
the playbook was we've got people in developers  

254
00:22:26,040 --> 00:22:32,680
or tech or IT. They choose Atlassian apps, 
they love them. They start to recommend them  

255
00:22:32,680 --> 00:22:38,360
to people in the business, and we start to see 
adoption, bottom-up adoption across the company  

256
00:22:38,360 --> 00:22:48,200
before people decide to standardize on Atlassian.
We made the bet that we can apply this playbook  

257
00:22:48,200 --> 00:22:56,000
to this market, which is basically we can, from 
people to use Jira, introduce HipChat, and then  

258
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:01,400
people will go into HipChat first in tech teams, 
and then it will expand into business teams,  

259
00:23:01,400 --> 00:23:08,280
and it'll go world to world basically from that. 
The thing is we didn't, in my opinion, do enough  

260
00:23:08,280 --> 00:23:17,680
to validate that assumption early enough. We did 
a lot of work, a lot of work even on other things,  

261
00:23:17,680 --> 00:23:24,320
even when faced with signals that this might 
not work. I do remember talking with a lot  

262
00:23:24,320 --> 00:23:31,400
of customers who were like, "Well, we've got, the 
IT is on HipChat, but the business prefer Slack."  

263
00:23:31,400 --> 00:23:37,560
And then we started to see those businesses 
choosing Slack, which is the, initially it was  

264
00:23:37,560 --> 00:23:42,280
like the developers try things and they like it 
and then everyone starts to adopt. In that case,  

265
00:23:42,280 --> 00:23:48,560
the Slack managed to create a very strong 
fund base in roles that were not tech and IT. 

266
00:23:48,560 --> 00:23:54,200
It was the moment where the consumerization of 
apps, that trend was starting to get really high.  

267
00:23:54,200 --> 00:24:00,680
Slack really rode that and they focused everything 
in their experience to catch that. They gamified  

268
00:24:00,680 --> 00:24:06,160
onboarding, they focused a lot more on the 
look and feel. They try to make it pleasant,  

269
00:24:06,160 --> 00:24:11,800
modern, functional to use. There's a lot of stuff 
that we learned since then from what they did,  

270
00:24:11,800 --> 00:24:19,320
we had missed that part. The part that I took 
personally from that is that there's a lot of  

271
00:24:19,320 --> 00:24:23,680
assumptions in what made us successful, 
it doesn't mean that it's going to work.

272
00:24:23,680 --> 00:24:27,480
Just I understand what you're saying, which is 
really interesting that Atlassian was really  

273
00:24:27,480 --> 00:24:32,600
successful selling basically to the buyer 
within the org, the IT team because they  

274
00:24:32,600 --> 00:24:37,640
had everything they needed. They checked all the 
checkboxes, but it turned out in the Slack case,  

275
00:24:37,640 --> 00:24:42,560
it was the users that ended up having the 
most influence over what tool they'd opted.

276
00:24:42,560 --> 00:24:47,480
I'd actually phrase it more as both were going 
after the users. Atlassian was going after the  

277
00:24:47,480 --> 00:24:53,120
users in tech teams, Slack was going after the 
users in business teams. And in both cases,  

278
00:24:53,120 --> 00:24:58,560
what happened was a bottom-up adoption. The 
people on the other side, the business would  

279
00:24:58,560 --> 00:25:04,200
prefer Slack, the developers, they prefer the 
HipChat. We did a lot of work in the streams  

280
00:25:04,200 --> 00:25:08,920
I was working on. We're integrating with every 
developer tooling out there to make sure that  

281
00:25:08,920 --> 00:25:13,600
every tool that they use goes into HipChat and 
from HipChat back to those tools. And basically,  

282
00:25:13,600 --> 00:25:20,280
they can do a lot of work by seeing an activity 
stream in HipChat. Business? Eh, not so excited  

283
00:25:20,280 --> 00:25:25,920
by this. Emojis, a lot of other things that 
may at some point I remember we were thinking  

284
00:25:25,920 --> 00:25:30,760
those things were trivial. No, they were not 
trivial. It was just a different approach for  

285
00:25:30,760 --> 00:25:35,880
using the tool by a different set of 
users that we did not talk enough to.

286
00:25:35,880 --> 00:25:41,040
So is the lesson here, don't underestimate the 
challenge you'll have convincing a new segment  

287
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:46,320
to buy your thing. You may think they're 
close or similar, but they're probably not.

288
00:25:46,320 --> 00:25:51,640
Yeah, that's one of them. The other one 
is what took you here is not going to  

289
00:25:51,640 --> 00:25:58,400
take you there. And so go back and try to 
explain why you are successful today, and  

290
00:25:58,400 --> 00:26:03,720
then if you think you can use the same thing 
on the next thing, find ways to validate it,  

291
00:26:03,720 --> 00:26:08,520
find ways to test it. Don't just go and 
build on those assumptions. That's the  

292
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:15,560
main thing I got out of this ordeal 
basically for the stuff I did after.

293
00:26:15,560 --> 00:26:18,320
How would you do that? How would you go 
about and test it? Is it use research?  

294
00:26:18,320 --> 00:26:22,720
Is it the PMs talking to potential 
users? What would you have done there?

295
00:26:22,720 --> 00:26:26,480
For example, when we started Jira for the 
Discovery, which is, so maybe I should  

296
00:26:26,480 --> 00:26:32,000
introduce this for a second. It's a product 
for product managers, which is mainly used for  

297
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:40,160
prioritization and roadmap. People use Jira 
to plan and track work when it's committed.  

298
00:26:40,160 --> 00:26:46,240
We wanted to create a space before that so 
people debate priorities with everyone that  

299
00:26:46,240 --> 00:26:50,520
should be involved in that prioritization 
process, whether it be the developers,  

300
00:26:50,520 --> 00:26:55,440
designers, so people in the product team 
or people outside of it, customer success,  

301
00:26:55,440 --> 00:27:01,800
salespeople, support, leadership and so on and 
so forth. When we started, that we thought, okay,  

302
00:27:01,800 --> 00:27:08,040
the product managers are already in Jira. You know 
what? We can reach them. So we create the tool,  

303
00:27:08,040 --> 00:27:13,000
and then we'll distribute it from Jira. We 
could have gone down the path of building  

304
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:18,000
that and then started to start to distribute it.
Instead, we did things like before we brought a  

305
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:24,280
single line of code, put an ad inside a Jira 
newsletter going, "Hey, we've got this thing  

306
00:27:24,280 --> 00:27:30,520
for product managers coming up." And then we 
had a website that before we had any line of  

307
00:27:30,520 --> 00:27:36,680
code written that said, "Hey, product managers, 
your job is hard. We want to help, put your name  

308
00:27:36,680 --> 00:27:41,160
here if you want to join us on the journey," 
that kind of thing. And that's when we saw,  

309
00:27:41,160 --> 00:27:45,680
I think it was in two weeks, we got more than 
3000 signups to that waitlist. We're like, "Okay,  

310
00:27:45,680 --> 00:27:51,680
cool. Validation of demand." We are talking 
to people who are interested and we can reach  

311
00:27:51,680 --> 00:28:00,520
them. That's one examples of the things that I 
tried later, just to make sure that we validate  

312
00:28:00,520 --> 00:28:06,360
the hypothesis that we've got much earlier on in 
the game basically, and not once it's too late.

313
00:28:06,360 --> 00:28:09,280
Awesome. That's an awesome, very tactical example.

314
00:28:09,280 --> 00:28:14,600
Yeah, most of those are, none of what I'm going 
to talk about today is revolutionary. A lot  

315
00:28:14,600 --> 00:28:18,520
of it is just trying to apply, asking 
the right question at the right time,  

316
00:28:18,520 --> 00:28:21,800
and trying to go by whatever 
means to answer it really.

317
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:26,560
Any other lessons from the HipChat experience 
before we shift to a different product?

318
00:28:26,560 --> 00:28:34,760
I've got two, I'm going to do them quickly. The 
first one is competitive myopia, don't fall for  

319
00:28:34,760 --> 00:28:42,160
it. At some point, the Slack was really gaining 
round and gaining round and capturing more of the  

320
00:28:42,160 --> 00:28:46,040
mindshare. And everyone on Twitter was always 
loving them. Even when they had outrages,  

321
00:28:46,040 --> 00:28:52,560
they were getting congratulated. I was like, 
"This is working mad." But the love was so strong,  

322
00:28:52,560 --> 00:28:57,480
and the way we tended to revert back is to 
our functional side of the brain going, okay,  

323
00:28:57,480 --> 00:29:00,440
we just need this one more feature. 
We just need this one more feature,  

324
00:29:00,440 --> 00:29:04,069
we just need this one more feature. 
And we ended up reacting to whatever.

325
00:29:04,069 --> 00:29:05,120
... more feature. We just need this one more 
feature. And we ended up reacting to whatever the  

326
00:29:05,120 --> 00:29:09,440
competitor was doing, which I think is really, 
really bad because that's when we lost basically  

327
00:29:10,080 --> 00:29:17,240
what made HipChat successful so far, which is to 
serve some users really well. And instead we ended  

328
00:29:17,240 --> 00:29:22,840
up fast following based on what the competitor was 
doing, which is super bad because your competitor,  

329
00:29:22,840 --> 00:29:27,320
if you think of what they do as an iceberg, 
the top side, what comes out of the water  

330
00:29:27,320 --> 00:29:31,360
is what they've shipped in terms of features, 
but it's based on all this stuff that they've  

331
00:29:31,360 --> 00:29:36,920
built in terms of research and understanding of 
their customer base and everything else. And so  

332
00:29:36,920 --> 00:29:41,840
you're just seeing the manifestation of what 
they were thinking maybe a year ago, based on  

333
00:29:41,840 --> 00:29:49,000
what they're shipping now. But we got there.
And now whenever I work, I tend to try and  

334
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:54,360
ignore competition other than watching every 
three months or so, seeing what came out,  

335
00:29:54,360 --> 00:29:59,200
if there's anything we should be worried about, 
afraid of, stuff like that. But really just  

336
00:29:59,200 --> 00:30:05,400
try to disconnect all the creative process and 
the research process from what competitors do,  

337
00:30:05,400 --> 00:30:11,000
because you can't compare. The market is huge. 
There are hundreds of thousands of companies  

338
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:16,200
out there. Not everyone has the same needs. We 
serve a particular set of segments. We would do  

339
00:30:16,200 --> 00:30:20,760
better learning from them to then expand to the 
others than watching what competition is doing.

340
00:30:20,760 --> 00:30:23,720
And this is advice you give to your 
teams, just ignore the competition,  

341
00:30:23,720 --> 00:30:26,560
maybe pay attention at big 
announcements and things like that?

342
00:30:26,560 --> 00:30:31,040
We always see in the Slack Channels team 
sharing, okay, they just did this with AI,  

343
00:30:31,040 --> 00:30:36,640
they just did that. So it keeps coming up, 
and so we often have discussions to go back,  

344
00:30:36,640 --> 00:30:43,400
to okay, let's watch again the user 
interviews that we did over the past  

345
00:30:43,400 --> 00:30:48,720
three weeks. Let's watch them all together now 
and remember who we are building this for. So  

346
00:30:48,720 --> 00:30:54,880
there's a lot of trying to anchor back on 
what we know and how, basically building  

347
00:30:54,880 --> 00:30:58,200
our own journey on it. And I think it's 
much richer for everyone to be involved.

348
00:30:58,200 --> 00:31:01,520
I love that. So you're finding that when 
there's a big announcement and everyone's like,  

349
00:31:01,520 --> 00:31:05,240
"Oh my God, look what Slack's doing," or 
"Look what this company's doing." It's like,  

350
00:31:05,240 --> 00:31:07,880
"Okay, now let's spend a little time 
reminding ourselves what our customers  

351
00:31:07,880 --> 00:31:11,080
have been asking us to do and let's 
watch a couple of user interviews."

352
00:31:11,080 --> 00:31:14,760
And even when there is something that competitors 
do that is right, remember, we're playing the  

353
00:31:14,760 --> 00:31:23,400
long run and we don't always need to be first and 
shinier. We need to make sure that people have a  

354
00:31:23,400 --> 00:31:27,760
problem, we solve this problem. They tell us, we 
solve this problem for them. They are delighted  

355
00:31:27,760 --> 00:31:32,600
when we solve these problems for them. And so 
that's the stuff we should be obsessing about.

356
00:31:32,600 --> 00:31:37,160
I love that. And you said you had 
one more lesson from this experience.

357
00:31:37,160 --> 00:31:43,560
Yeah, the last one, startups have the benefit 
of starving. Right? We're a big company,  

358
00:31:43,560 --> 00:31:48,680
we can throw a lot of resources at something that 
we're excited about. So this notion of we rebuild  

359
00:31:48,680 --> 00:31:54,880
the HipChat, was coupled with we rebuild the 
HipChat and we'll do this on a new platform,  

360
00:31:54,880 --> 00:31:59,520
which is microservices and everything that 
we built can be reused across all the other  

361
00:31:59,520 --> 00:32:05,400
products. So the chat text box that you've got, 
it's an editor that can be open full screen and  

362
00:32:05,400 --> 00:32:10,440
it's a Confluence editor with everything that you 
can do there. It's built as a platform component,  

363
00:32:10,440 --> 00:32:14,640
which is amazing when the platform is there when 
you start building the product. Where it's really  

364
00:32:14,640 --> 00:32:21,280
difficult is when you try to do the two at the 
same time. So I think that part, if I were to work  

365
00:32:21,280 --> 00:32:27,840
on HipChat again and say I was leading that thing, 
that's the part I would go, okay, we need to win  

366
00:32:29,640 --> 00:32:35,240
the problem space first, and if the platform 
is there, let's use it. If it's not there,  

367
00:32:35,240 --> 00:32:41,960
we'll hack it, test it, iterate on it with 
customers, and then whatever is good there,  

368
00:32:41,960 --> 00:32:57,911
let's platformize it later.
But that's where you see what  

369
00:32:57,910 --> 00:32:58,076
makes us super powerful as a bigger company, 
can also slow us down and make us focus on the  

370
00:32:58,077 --> 00:32:59,360
wrong assumptions. So in that case, I think we 
thought we will win. Interestingly, I think we  

371
00:32:59,360 --> 00:33:04,680
were convinced that we had a great shot at this 
market. And at the same time we thought that we  

372
00:33:04,680 --> 00:33:11,080
could tackle the rewrite and we could tackle the 
platformization. All these things were necessary,  

373
00:33:11,080 --> 00:33:16,880
but all of them at the same time was probably 
a bit too much to bite. Now I'm saying that,  

374
00:33:16,880 --> 00:33:24,840
but today the editor you see in Confluence started 
with what we did in HipChat back then. So I would  

375
00:33:24,840 --> 00:33:31,080
say that in terms of code, purely in terms of 
code, 70% of what we wrote for HipChat is probably  

376
00:33:31,080 --> 00:33:37,480
still in the Atlassian platform today. But for 
a new bet, local Optima, that was really bad.

377
00:33:37,480 --> 00:33:42,040
Yeah. Just thinking about the fact that 
Atlassian could have had this $30 billion  

378
00:33:42,040 --> 00:33:46,720
business if this worked out, and I could 
see why people would be frustrated that it  

379
00:33:46,720 --> 00:33:52,480
didn't work out. So thank you for sharing 
that story. Let's talk about Statuspage,  

380
00:33:52,480 --> 00:33:57,720
another journey that you were a part of, that also 
didn't quite work out the way folks had hoped.  

381
00:33:59,240 --> 00:34:03,840
Our therapy session continues. Talk about 
what that product was and what happened there.

382
00:34:03,840 --> 00:34:05,840
Yeah, so this one is actually a success story,  

383
00:34:05,840 --> 00:34:10,080
but became a success story after 
I was gone [inaudible 00:34:08]

384
00:34:10,080 --> 00:34:10,600
Okay.

385
00:34:10,600 --> 00:34:16,480
That's more like a story of big companies can 
play the long run and for you individually  

386
00:34:16,480 --> 00:34:23,880
inside that process, it might look like a loss 
and you might feel like you're going nowhere,  

387
00:34:23,880 --> 00:34:28,000
yet the company stays on the opportunity for 
long enough to make it happen. So what we're  

388
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:32,200
going to talk about here are my own challenges 
working through it for something that ended up  

389
00:34:32,200 --> 00:34:37,560
being very successful in the end, but I 
felt as a failure personally back then.  

390
00:34:37,560 --> 00:34:45,640
So Statuspage at some point... So Jira is 
used by developers, right? And back then,  

391
00:34:45,640 --> 00:34:52,160
I think it was back in 2016 or even before that, 
2015, everyone was moving to the cloud, everyone  

392
00:34:52,160 --> 00:34:59,080
was adopting DevOps, you build it, you run it. So 
basically developers would implement the software  

393
00:34:59,080 --> 00:35:02,760
and then they would put it to production. 
And after they put it to production, they  

394
00:35:02,760 --> 00:35:08,400
don't throw it over the wall to operations people. 
It's the same developers who operate the software  

395
00:35:08,400 --> 00:35:15,440
in production. They go on call, yada yada.
So back then I did market research to see  

396
00:35:15,440 --> 00:35:21,200
whether Atlassian should play there, whether 
we had a crack at going after all the jobs  

397
00:35:21,200 --> 00:35:27,800
around IT operations. So Jira was basically 
Jira software to build software. Could we  

398
00:35:27,800 --> 00:35:33,720
have Jira for operations? So for operating this 
software. And so I did market research, found a  

399
00:35:33,720 --> 00:35:37,920
few companies that were doing super interesting 
things there, like [inaudible 00:35:37], Opsgenie,  

400
00:35:37,920 --> 00:35:45,520
New Relic. BigPanda was a small startup doing 
lots of cool stuff there, and Statuspage. Now  

401
00:35:45,520 --> 00:35:53,080
I discovered Statuspage and found their offering 
super interesting, in that Atlassian is not an  

402
00:35:53,080 --> 00:35:59,360
operations... We don't really build super deep 
operations tooling, what we focus on a lot is  

403
00:35:59,360 --> 00:36:06,040
the collaborative aspects around everything. 
And when I was watching teams in incidents,  

404
00:36:06,040 --> 00:36:12,320
I realized that there's a lot of chicken without 
a head syndrome, headless chicken, people running  

405
00:36:12,320 --> 00:36:17,360
around like bunch of headless chicken.
Shit hits the fan, and then what you  

406
00:36:17,360 --> 00:36:23,320
see is teams just scrambling and everything 
gets mixed up all together in trying to fix  

407
00:36:23,320 --> 00:36:27,800
the problem straight away, but at the same time 
questioning what happened, arguing over why we got  

408
00:36:27,800 --> 00:36:32,680
there. Your boss is pinging you to go, "Hey, 
what's going on? I've been hearing that the app  

409
00:36:32,680 --> 00:36:38,440
is down. We're losing money." Customers are 
emailing you and asking you what's going...  

410
00:36:38,440 --> 00:36:43,440
Your support channels get blown up. Sales people 
are worried because their customers are calling  

411
00:36:43,440 --> 00:36:48,440
them. So basically, it ends up being a 
super stressful experience for everyone. 

412
00:36:48,440 --> 00:36:52,680
And what Statuspage was offering is something 
seemingly super simple, which is, well,  

413
00:36:52,680 --> 00:36:58,160
what you should have is a status page for your 
services and you tell your customers about it  

414
00:36:58,160 --> 00:37:03,560
and you can subscribe to your status page. Over 
there, you've got your services, and for those  

415
00:37:03,560 --> 00:37:10,680
services you can publish an incident whenever 
there is one, and your customers will be notified,  

416
00:37:10,680 --> 00:37:13,920
which means that they're not going to get in 
touch with support because they know you're on  

417
00:37:13,920 --> 00:37:22,000
it. It's going to build trust with them because 
basically you are open in your communication with  

418
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:27,320
them. They're more likely to empathize with your 
position and be supportive as opposed to, "Oh,  

419
00:37:27,320 --> 00:37:31,400
that stuff is done again." So there 
was just so many benefits of that.

420
00:37:31,400 --> 00:37:34,520
I'm going to share a quick story 
while you're on this topic.

421
00:37:34,520 --> 00:37:35,480
Yeah, of course.

422
00:37:35,480 --> 00:37:42,360
Funny enough, a decade ago, I used to work 
at a website performance monitoring company  

423
00:37:42,360 --> 00:37:49,120
and I started a blog called Transparent Uptime. 
And my whole blog was about the power of being  

424
00:37:49,120 --> 00:37:55,040
transparent about being down, telling people the 
status of things are broken right now, here's when  

425
00:37:55,040 --> 00:38:00,160
things are going to return. It was a whole thing 
I was really obsessed with, and I was deep into  

426
00:38:00,160 --> 00:38:04,480
this space. So when I saw Statuspage back in the 
day and Atlassian working, I was like, "I love  

427
00:38:04,480 --> 00:38:07,760
this." And I actually chatted with the founders 
a bit, because they were fans of that work I was  

428
00:38:07,760 --> 00:38:13,200
doing back in the day. Completely unrelated 
to anything else I've done in my life. But  

429
00:38:13,200 --> 00:38:19,400
I was really passionate about this very strange 
topic and I love that companies are embracing it.

430
00:38:20,840 --> 00:38:26,080
I really loved diving deep into it for a few 
years, it's an amazing topic. And so anyway,  

431
00:38:26,080 --> 00:38:30,360
there's so many fascinating things about 
this particular domain, but back then... So  

432
00:38:30,360 --> 00:38:36,680
find Statuspage and we invited a few of those 
companies to work with us for a week to go,  

433
00:38:36,680 --> 00:38:41,360
hey, so we're at Atlassian, we're basically 
the collaboration hub for everything that  

434
00:38:41,360 --> 00:38:46,360
happens for developing teams. What would an 
experience look like that puts everything  

435
00:38:46,360 --> 00:38:49,800
together and where [inaudible 00:38:48] could 
actually help you get the right information  

436
00:38:49,800 --> 00:38:55,120
to the right team so they can act on it?
And so we did a week of hackathon in San Francisco  

437
00:38:55,120 --> 00:39:03,640
all together. So people from New Relic, Statuspage 
and a few other companies. And out of that came  

438
00:39:03,640 --> 00:39:09,800
really interesting concepts and there was really 
something there and I was like, "Okay, I should  

439
00:39:09,800 --> 00:39:17,880
start to work on a business case for Atlassian for 
basically IT tool/operations." Now, big companies  

440
00:39:17,880 --> 00:39:24,280
like Atlassian, we've got money. So in every 
strategy that we've got, we've got cash in the  

441
00:39:24,280 --> 00:39:32,000
bank, we always look at should we build, should we 
buy, should we partner? Acquisitions can be really  

442
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:36,160
powerful to accelerate you. We've got quite a few 
