444
00:39:44,320 --> 00:39:49,160
and I was running the integration of the 
Statuspage business inside the Atlassian business.

445
00:39:49,160 --> 00:39:53,360
Thanks for sharing all that context. What 
are some of the things that you learned from  

446
00:39:53,360 --> 00:39:57,000
going through this experience? It sounds like 
basically it was really painful when you were  

447
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:02,560
a part of it and then it ended up being really 
successful. What are some lessons from the pain?

448
00:40:02,560 --> 00:40:08,000
My learnings from it were on the acquisition 
side. So big company, we've got cash,  

449
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:13,440
we can buy a company, it will make us go 
faster, is not always the case. In my case,  

450
00:40:13,440 --> 00:40:18,200
there were quite a few things that were not 
as easy as I would've thought. The first one  

451
00:40:18,200 --> 00:40:24,400
is the culture shock of a startup that joins your 
company. So imagine you're a startup, you've got,  

452
00:40:24,400 --> 00:40:29,280
I don't know, 20, 30 staff or something and 
things are going well, and you are in full  

453
00:40:29,280 --> 00:40:36,240
control of your destiny. And then a company buys 
you to accelerate you, but then you stop owning  

454
00:40:36,240 --> 00:40:43,160
all the decisions. So the CEO, maybe you become 
a product person. The person who was running GTM  

455
00:40:43,160 --> 00:40:48,400
but was also doing a bunch of product stuff, and 
was also doing a bunch of maybe engineering stuff,  

456
00:40:48,400 --> 00:40:55,040
all of a sudden is just working in marketing.
There are decisions that are made above your  

457
00:40:55,040 --> 00:41:02,600
head. For example, portfolio fit, which should 
be part of your product, which is things that  

458
00:41:02,600 --> 00:41:07,320
should be used from the platform that we've got. 
So there's a lot of decisions that we're able to  

459
00:41:07,320 --> 00:41:14,880
make on the day-to-day basis, that start to 
escape you. Big companies look much further  

460
00:41:14,880 --> 00:41:22,640
out in the future. So Atlassian would look at the 
long game. And so I remember with Statuspage when  

461
00:41:22,640 --> 00:41:25,800
they first joined, we asked about the roadmaps 
and they were like, well, for the next three  

462
00:41:25,800 --> 00:41:30,760
months we're working on that and for the following 
three months we're thinking about potentially X,  

463
00:41:30,760 --> 00:41:35,600
Y or Z. And so when we're like, "Okay, so what's 
the three-year plan?" They're like, "What do you  

464
00:41:35,600 --> 00:41:43,120
mean the three-year plan? I don't know, we'll 
survive, I guess." Which is what startups do. And  

465
00:41:43,120 --> 00:41:49,320
they were very penciled ideas about the future, 
but not to the extent of what a big company would  

466
00:41:49,320 --> 00:41:56,520
expect. And so that's a really big culture shock.
And what you end up with as well, and that's for  

467
00:41:56,520 --> 00:42:01,480
companies who are looking to get acquired out 
there or buying other companies, before, you  

468
00:42:01,480 --> 00:42:07,880
had a startup and everyone was one team, depending 
on how the buying company is organized, you might  

469
00:42:07,880 --> 00:42:13,720
land with silos from within your team. So the 
way Atlassian is organized is like many Atlassian  

470
00:42:13,720 --> 00:42:18,000
companies, we've got a product organization, 
we've got an engineering organization, we've  

471
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:22,840
got a marketing organization, design organization, 
and they each roll up to a different leader which  

472
00:42:22,840 --> 00:42:28,000
may then roll up to the same person, but still by 
and large different organizations that are then  

473
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:33,360
assembled into squads and those squads operate 
together. But there are rituals that are part of  

474
00:42:33,360 --> 00:42:42,680
the squad and there are rituals that ladder up to 
where you are in terms of craft. So I do remember  

475
00:42:42,680 --> 00:42:47,520
how daunting it was for the Statuspage team when 
they joined, to understand how to navigate that. 

476
00:42:47,520 --> 00:42:53,400
If I want to hire a new designer, I'm not 
talking to the Statuspage CEO anymore,  

477
00:42:53,400 --> 00:43:00,280
I need to talk to the head of design for this 
area, which has pretty much nothing to do with  

478
00:43:00,280 --> 00:43:07,000
the Statuspage business up until the acquisition. 
So that is the things that people told me when I  

479
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:11,000
started working on the integration, which 
is, hey, remember, you don't know yet,  

480
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:16,000
but integrations are mostly about people. They're 
not about technology as much or product vision.  

481
00:43:16,800 --> 00:43:22,360
All of that stuff is the easy stuff. The hard part 
is the people. And I didn't quite understand at  

482
00:43:22,360 --> 00:43:29,240
first and then I really got it by the end of it.
Because what we tell those companies is we can  

483
00:43:29,240 --> 00:43:34,480
accelerate by buying, but in reality they are 
going to be faced with more internal processes  

484
00:43:34,480 --> 00:43:39,080
around how they manage staff, performance 
reviews, this concept of engineering allocation,  

485
00:43:39,080 --> 00:43:47,040
revenue forecasts, OKRs, long-term roadmaps, 
all that stuff comes in very new to them.  

486
00:43:47,040 --> 00:43:52,640
So one part of the company top-down says, 
we bought you because you are successful,  

487
00:43:52,640 --> 00:43:58,880
keep doing what you're doing. While many other 
teams without meaning to, basically end up  

488
00:43:58,880 --> 00:44:03,520
constantly interacting so that the right processes 
are followed, so that the right things are done.

489
00:44:03,520 --> 00:44:04,480
That's a really interesting point,  

490
00:44:04,480 --> 00:44:07,840
that one group is keep doing what you're 
doing. We're going to leave you alone,  

491
00:44:07,840 --> 00:44:11,800
you're the experts. And then other people that 
are on the ground actually building it are like,  

492
00:44:11,800 --> 00:44:15,600
"Hey, build with this component. Hey, we 
need this process, we need this document."

493
00:44:15,600 --> 00:44:21,840
And it's the things that you used to be able to 
focus 90% of your time working on your product,  

494
00:44:21,840 --> 00:44:26,480
and all of a sudden all of that stuff may 
seem parasitical but comes in and interrupts  

495
00:44:26,480 --> 00:44:33,760
you all the time. And often the new joiners, they 
don't know that they basically are not only being  

496
00:44:33,760 --> 00:44:37,840
acquired, they've been hired by the company. 
So they basically are joining a different  

497
00:44:37,840 --> 00:44:42,160
company with different sets of rituals, with a 
different culture. All of that is very different,  

498
00:44:42,160 --> 00:44:46,080
basically. It's not going to be the same 
for every acquisition. Like I said, we had  

499
00:44:46,080 --> 00:44:51,920
some acquisitions that were great. Statuspage 
ended up being a huge success inside Atlassian,  

500
00:44:51,920 --> 00:44:56,080
but when I was there, I basically worked through 
the difficult parts of it, where I was like,  

501
00:44:56,080 --> 00:45:01,040
"It's not as simple as people may think." So one 
warning, if you're planning to do acquisitions,  

502
00:45:01,040 --> 00:45:08,520
make sure you factor all of that in and think 
about the integration plans to compensate for  

503
00:45:08,520 --> 00:45:11,840
these aspects. So you don't expect the 
business to join and keep running at  

504
00:45:11,840 --> 00:45:16,920
exactly the same pace, because going to be 
a big slowdown before it accelerates again.

505
00:45:16,920 --> 00:45:20,640
So maybe as a last question here, is just 
say you were to do an acquisition again and  

506
00:45:20,640 --> 00:45:23,400
I don't know if you've gone through more, 
what's one thing you would change? What's  

507
00:45:23,400 --> 00:45:26,960
one thing you'd recommend of let's make 
sure to do this thing very differently?

508
00:45:27,520 --> 00:45:32,000
One aspect that I'm going to talk about 
to then go there, but one aspect we didn't  

509
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:36,680
talk about which is we bought a product, how 
does that product fit with the rest? And so  

510
00:45:37,600 --> 00:45:42,760
we had different types of acquisitions that we 
did. One is we buy the company and we keep the  

511
00:45:42,760 --> 00:45:46,760
product running and then we try to integrate 
it with our tech stack. And then the other  

512
00:45:46,760 --> 00:45:51,440
acquisition is we buy the company and then we 
kind of rebuild on our platform, or we buy with  

513
00:45:51,440 --> 00:45:58,440
this huge synergy with our platform. And so we 
call that the frankenstack, otherwise. Which is,  

514
00:45:58,440 --> 00:46:02,440
you get one tech stack here, one tech stack 
there and they can't quite talk to each other,  

515
00:46:02,440 --> 00:46:07,200
identity is different, integrating is different. 
And so it looks like a patchwork of products and  

516
00:46:07,200 --> 00:46:14,240
that's not what our customers want from us.
So the next time I try personally, I would  

517
00:46:14,240 --> 00:46:22,520
treat it like hiring over treating it like buying 
business only. So there would be a huge component  

518
00:46:22,520 --> 00:46:29,480
which is to both educate and tease out what 
it means to actually hire the team inside the  

519
00:46:29,480 --> 00:46:34,680
company. At the same time I'm saying that because 
I don't want to do a big one. The next one I want  

520
00:46:34,680 --> 00:46:41,320
to do is relatively small. Find a company that has 
amazing product that we can bring in as a tech-in,  

521
00:46:41,320 --> 00:46:45,440
shut down the product, rebuild it on our 
platform and so it's basically the equivalent  

522
00:46:45,440 --> 00:46:51,280
of an acqui-hire, because basically what we'll 
be buying is the acceleration of our roadmap. 

523
00:46:51,280 --> 00:46:57,680
We could try and form a team to do what they did, 
but they've been successful so they know what  

524
00:46:57,680 --> 00:47:02,400
they're doing. We could probably get there one 
year faster. What does that mean for our revenue  

525
00:47:02,400 --> 00:47:07,840
at the scale of Atlassian, if we can enter a 
market one year earlier? It's probably going  

526
00:47:07,840 --> 00:47:16,200
to pay the acquisition back on its own. So my 
learnings from it were basically that it needs to  

527
00:47:16,200 --> 00:47:22,560
be treated like hiring and what I would like to do 
next time is more doing it like that, basically.

528
00:47:22,560 --> 00:47:25,880
What about in the case of 
HipChat, where it feels like  

529
00:47:27,160 --> 00:47:32,920
it was a mistake to rebuild a thing. Is there 
for this kind of startup, don't rebuild for  

530
00:47:32,920 --> 00:47:36,320
this kind of startup? Start again. Do you 
have a thought of how you separate those two?

531
00:47:36,320 --> 00:47:38,720
There's actually a big difference. 
There's a big difference. Which is  

532
00:47:38,720 --> 00:47:43,880
in one case what you try to do is.... So when 
you rebuild, you've got a successful business,  

533
00:47:43,880 --> 00:47:47,800
you've got hundreds of thousands of customers, 
for example, and you're trying to rebuild the  

534
00:47:47,800 --> 00:47:52,200
same thing or a different thing, but for the same 
customers that have got expectations about your  

535
00:47:52,200 --> 00:47:58,320
current product. In the other one is you buy a 
company that's got some traction, not too much,  

536
00:47:58,320 --> 00:48:05,960
so you can shut down the business and then rebuild 
on your platform to reach your customer base. So  

537
00:48:05,960 --> 00:48:11,800
it's not the same as trying to rebuild the plane 
mid flight, it's delaying takeoff. It's like,  

538
00:48:11,800 --> 00:48:17,120
"Yeah, we did a trial run, the plane landed. Okay, 
cool. Switch to another plane, takeoff again."

539
00:48:17,120 --> 00:48:20,560
Got it. I love that. Any other key insights and  

540
00:48:20,560 --> 00:48:25,200
lessons from this experience before 
we get to your product discovery?

541
00:48:25,200 --> 00:48:29,952
One last one and then I'm going to stop with the 
therapy session, thank you very much for offering.

542
00:48:29,952 --> 00:48:35,080
No, no, we got to keep it going. I got to 
rack up the bill on this therapy session.

543
00:48:35,080 --> 00:48:41,240
Which is, remember I mentioned I was working on a 
business case for... Basically going bigger in IT  

544
00:48:41,240 --> 00:48:45,800
operations. And so there was as Statuspage as part 
of it, but there was a lot of stuff that I wanted  

545
00:48:45,800 --> 00:48:51,400
to be able to do inside Jira and a whole bunch of 
other products to basically go big in that area,  

546
00:48:51,400 --> 00:48:58,320
IT operations, before Jira service management, 
which is a very successful product we've got  

547
00:48:58,320 --> 00:49:04,520
around that. Before it was really entering that 
part of the market. Everyone was excited. It was  

548
00:49:04,520 --> 00:49:11,120
before we had an incubator internally. And 
so I was trying to pitch it like let's build  

549
00:49:11,120 --> 00:49:16,400
a new product that's centered around that 
