909
01:20:57,320 --> 01:21:02,360
we would not have done that. And we would've had 
a hard time justifying it, but because it was not,  

910
01:21:02,360 --> 01:21:10,040
we basically gave ourselves the stamp to 
be able to do it. So still in don't fuck  

911
01:21:10,040 --> 01:21:16,320
existing customers, something I read from a site, 
from Reforge that talk about the Safety Funnel. 

912
01:21:16,320 --> 01:21:20,800
So they have this thing where the typical 
growth funnel goes from acquisition all  

913
01:21:20,800 --> 01:21:24,960
the way to revenue and there's a whole bunch 
of different stages in between. Your goal is  

914
01:21:24,960 --> 01:21:28,920
to maximize the number of people who 
go through this funnel successfully. 

915
01:21:28,920 --> 01:21:32,880
And I was trying to explain to people what we 
were trying to do with Jira Product Discovery,  

916
01:21:32,880 --> 01:21:38,320
and I was struggling to put a name on it. 
And it was we're going to work with a few,  

917
01:21:38,320 --> 01:21:43,040
small number of customers up until it's right 
for them and then we're going to expose it to  

918
01:21:43,040 --> 01:21:48,720
progressively more people. And I know it's very 
common sense, but that's basically what we decided  

919
01:21:48,720 --> 01:21:54,960
to do instead of the Atlassian way, which was 
more, "Hey, we measure our success based on..."  

920
01:21:54,960 --> 01:21:59,280
For example, at that time, I think it was still 
before all those projects, "... monthly active  

921
01:21:59,280 --> 01:22:03,560
users." If that was a measure of success, we 
would've been pushed very quickly to go and  

922
01:22:03,560 --> 01:22:07,120
expose it to as many people as we could. We 
didn't want to do that because if they would  

923
01:22:07,120 --> 01:22:11,000
have a bad experience, it would've been 
very hard to claim them back afterwards. 

924
01:22:11,000 --> 01:22:17,040
So someone in Reforge put the name on Safety 
Funnel. So the Safety Funnel is amazing. People  

925
01:22:17,040 --> 01:22:21,640
don't understand that. You basically put a hard 
stop and you limit the number of people who had  

926
01:22:21,640 --> 01:22:26,800
bad experiences. And you do that for a while, 
up until you can prove it's amazing and then you  

927
01:22:26,800 --> 01:22:33,440
invite more people. So we did a lot of that. So 
we basically created that pocket away from Jira  

928
01:22:33,440 --> 01:22:37,800
to reimagine what Jira could be for product 
managers. And we only exposed that to a very  

929
01:22:37,800 --> 01:22:45,640
small number of customers at first. So that's 
don't fuck existing customers' first principle.

930
01:22:45,640 --> 01:22:48,160
And the reason that's important, 
just to put a point there,  

931
01:22:48,160 --> 01:22:53,320
is the business will start to get upset 
if you're making many customers upset.

932
01:22:53,320 --> 01:22:56,880
That would've been it if we had 
triggered an incident that brought  

933
01:22:56,880 --> 01:23:01,120
down Jira for millions of users. And 
first time might have been okay. I mean,  

934
01:23:01,120 --> 01:23:05,480
by the third time we would've been 
asked to pack up and go home, I think.

935
01:23:05,480 --> 01:23:10,840
Got it. So the advice there is just limit how many 
people get exposed to your very early product,  

936
01:23:10,840 --> 01:23:14,000
even if it's going to hurt your numbers. 
You don't want to cause people to be like,  

937
01:23:14,000 --> 01:23:16,480
"What the hell are you doing over 
there, man? [inaudible 01:23:17]."

938
01:23:16,480 --> 01:23:20,160
So [inaudible 01:23:17] your numbers is now the 
interesting one. So how do you frame success  

939
01:23:20,160 --> 01:23:24,840
and how do you define metrics when your goal is 
basically to work with a small number of customers  

940
01:23:24,840 --> 01:23:32,480
for a super long time? So that's what I ended 
up defining for this, is based on a term that  

941
01:23:32,480 --> 01:23:38,320
was used at Atlassian that I tried to formalize 
it into something that everyone could refer to,  

942
01:23:38,320 --> 01:23:44,080
which is the Lighthouse Users Program. And 
so the principle for it is it's a program,  

943
01:23:44,080 --> 01:23:49,800
so it's an official thing. We have hundreds 
of thousands of customers at Atlassian,  

944
01:23:49,800 --> 01:23:56,640
but we would only build the experience for a small 
number of them. And so there are stages to it. 

945
01:23:56,640 --> 01:24:03,920
The first stage is we work with 10 and we prove 
that the problems that they had are the things  

946
01:24:03,920 --> 01:24:10,080
that we solved and where we spend most of the 
time for the first 10 Lighthouse Users is to  

947
01:24:10,080 --> 01:24:14,800
explain why they are the Lighthouse Users.
Everything that explains why we believe they  

948
01:24:14,800 --> 01:24:20,000
are a proxy for every customer that we serve 
afterwards. We then have this stage from 10  

949
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:25,680
to 100 where we recruit more customers, but 
we're still not in the fully self-service,  

950
01:24:25,680 --> 01:24:28,440
don't need a lot of onboarding stuff. 
We're still testing out the value,  

951
01:24:28,440 --> 01:24:33,240
but we're testing the different variations in 
the scenarios that people face to make sure  

952
01:24:33,240 --> 01:24:37,360
that the core solution that we've got can cater 
for those. So there's a lot of different options  

953
01:24:37,360 --> 01:24:44,320
and different security needs. There's a lot of 
subtleties that you catch between 10 and 100. 

954
01:24:44,320 --> 01:24:48,400
Then we get to a stage where we're like, "You 
know what? It's good. It solves people's problems,  

955
01:24:48,400 --> 01:24:52,200
but it's not self-service. We just need to 
explain stuff. We need to work with people  

956
01:24:52,200 --> 01:24:56,560
on Slack. We need to work with them and 
answer a lot of support tickets or do a  

957
01:24:56,560 --> 01:25:01,200
lot of Zoom calls to explain stuff."
Now we need to get from 100 to 1,000,  

958
01:25:02,200 --> 01:25:07,080
and by getting there we basically need 
to solve all of that and after that we  

959
01:25:07,080 --> 01:25:11,800
graduate. So basically by detailing that and 
explaining all the success criteria in between,  

960
01:25:11,800 --> 01:25:17,280
it helps to define success in that in the make 
phase, we've got 10, 100, 1,000, and then people  

961
01:25:17,280 --> 01:25:21,160
can understand exactly where we're at there, and 
the types of questions we're trying to answer.  

962
01:25:21,160 --> 01:25:28,880
In the 10, we're answering every question with a 
user, snippet of a video call with them, either  

963
01:25:28,880 --> 01:25:34,160
talking about their problem and solution but 
showing the product and how they solve with it. 

964
01:25:34,160 --> 01:25:39,960
That's how we wanted our stakeholders to view it, 
which is it's very qualitative, but have it felt  

965
01:25:39,960 --> 01:25:45,760
from the user's perspective. It's different 
when we go from 10 to 100, from 100 to 1,000,  

966
01:25:46,320 --> 01:25:53,440
but for each of those there's a playbook for 
how you go from one to the other. That helped  

967
01:25:53,440 --> 01:25:58,280
us because we could then clean the space to 
do the right thing and we will not ask to hit,  

968
01:25:58,280 --> 01:26:02,800
for example, a multi-active user's number or 
number of customers' number or percentage of  

969
01:26:02,800 --> 01:26:09,120
users who use this number. Because it's very 
qualitative still when we're at that stage.

970
01:26:09,120 --> 01:26:12,800
That is super cool and super interesting. 
And it's along the lines of the gates. It  

971
01:26:12,800 --> 01:26:16,800
aligns with, at each gate, here's how many 
users we're looking for. Basically, it sets  

972
01:26:16,800 --> 01:26:20,720
expectations for what success is, keeps you 
from having to scale things too early. It's  

973
01:26:20,720 --> 01:26:24,960
such a cool idea. And you call it Lighthouse 
Users, like the Lighthouse Users Program?

974
01:26:24,960 --> 01:26:30,640
Lighthouse Users, and there's two sides to it. 
We just talked about the stakeholder facing  

975
01:26:30,640 --> 01:26:38,640
side. The one I love is the team facing side 
of this, which is I've seen a lot of teams,  

976
01:26:38,640 --> 01:26:43,200
Atlassian and other companies as the 
products grow, you tend to leverage a lot  

977
01:26:43,200 --> 01:26:49,040
more user research, formal user research 
or CSAT service. And the way I call it,  

978
01:26:49,040 --> 01:26:54,600
it's hiding behind research and not being 
close enough to the ground with customers.  

979
01:26:54,600 --> 01:26:59,040
And what I want to do in the teams 
I work with is to create a direct  

980
01:26:59,040 --> 01:27:00,236
feedback loop with customers, but not like someone 
gives you feedback and you do it. We talk...

981
01:27:00,236 --> 01:27:03,760
... with customers, but not like someone gives 
you feedback and you do it. We talk to those  

982
01:27:03,760 --> 01:27:10,600
customers, we build stuff for them. So there's 
something I've seen which is climate change.  

983
01:27:10,600 --> 01:27:13,480
It's a thing. Everyone knows it's a thing. 
We all read reports about it. We're all  

984
01:27:13,480 --> 01:27:23,520
like ... Every time we read an IPCC report we're 
like, "Shit." Do we change anything? Not enough. 

985
01:27:23,520 --> 01:27:31,480
What makes people want to change and actually 
gives them a trigger to change? I've seen is  

986
01:27:31,480 --> 01:27:37,920
a lot more empathizing with individual 
people's experience. If I know someone  

987
01:27:37,920 --> 01:27:42,560
that's impacted by climate change, it's going 
to make me relate a lot more strongly to the  

988
01:27:42,560 --> 01:27:48,556
concept of climate change and want to change 
myself. Sorry for the power note here. I'm-

989
01:27:48,556 --> 01:27:52,480
No, that's such a good example. Such a good 
way of making that point very clear of just  

990
01:27:52,480 --> 01:27:58,400
the power of talking to a small number of users 
versus thinking that the more data you have,  

991
01:27:58,400 --> 01:28:02,240
looking at data, CSAT scores, NPS 
retention will tell you what you need.

992
01:28:02,240 --> 01:28:07,160
So what we do with that is we recruit 10 
people and we put these people in front of  

993
01:28:07,160 --> 01:28:14,480
the whole team, not just the PMs, PM, designer, 
engineering. We meet on Zoom, we chat, we work  

994
01:28:14,480 --> 01:28:20,000
with the same ones over months to build a product. 
They are with us on Slack. We have regular things. 

995
01:28:20,000 --> 01:28:24,640
What we've seen, what I've seen going 
fast is that the engineers would go into  

996
01:28:24,640 --> 01:28:28,640
a planning meeting and the PM would say, "So 
we should work on X," and the engineer will go,  

997
01:28:28,640 --> 01:28:31,960
"Wait a minute. We've had a talk with this 
customer and they struggle with this so I  

998
01:28:31,960 --> 01:28:35,520
think we should work on that instead and fix that 
part of the experience," and so on and so forth. 

999
01:28:35,520 --> 01:28:38,200
So all of a sudden you're not 
talking about a product manager,  

1000
01:28:38,200 --> 01:28:42,080
you're talking about a product team 
with product engineers. So there was  

1001
01:28:42,080 --> 01:28:46,520
this thing at Atlassian where we called some 
engineers were more like system engineers,  

1002
01:28:46,520 --> 01:28:51,200
some were more product engineers.
In my opinion everyone can be a product  

1003
01:28:51,200 --> 01:28:55,880
engineer. They just need to be exposed to the 
right user context. The right user context,  

1004
01:28:55,880 --> 01:28:59,960
what is it? It's 10 customers you 
know by name, you know their context,  

1005
01:28:59,960 --> 01:29:05,000
you know their problems. You can empathize with 
it. This empathy makes you want to act to change  

1006
01:29:05,000 --> 01:29:12,040
your product to solve their problem and you 
get really huge pride coming back out of it. 

1007
01:29:12,040 --> 01:29:19,000
It can seem counterintuitive in a company like 
Atlassian. 300,000 customers, right? We should  

1008
01:29:19,000 --> 01:29:24,640
build for them. Well, you can't, right? We're 
limited in our ability to make changes that  

1009
01:29:24,640 --> 01:29:31,880
will work for the vast majority so might as well 
embrace that. Embrace that we are indeed biased,  

1010
01:29:31,880 --> 01:29:38,520
that we are indeed reacting based on feelings, 
like wanting to help or not wanting to help or  

1011
01:29:38,520 --> 01:29:44,120
reacting strongly to what you've seen, but we 
are embracing that to try and build the best  

1012
01:29:44,120 --> 01:29:51,120
product possible. I've actually seen that the 
outcome is, so far on this product it's worked.

1013
01:29:51,120 --> 01:29:54,400
If you actually think about this from the 
perspective of how would a startup approach  

1014
01:29:54,400 --> 01:29:59,480
this? This is exactly how a company that's just 
starting out would approach it. So it makes  

1015
01:29:59,480 --> 01:30:04,200
tons of sense to think of it this way. It's just 
people don't actually do this. It's hard to do. 

1016
01:30:04,200 --> 01:30:08,400
This is a segue to a question I wanted to 
ask. So it took probably a long time for  

1017
01:30:08,400 --> 01:30:15,080
you to show real success, real progress, real 
like, "This is going to work." First of all  

1018
01:30:15,080 --> 01:30:19,600
how long was that period of just like, "This 
is probably not going to work too. Oh wow,  

1019
01:30:19,600 --> 01:30:25,440
maybe this is going to work"? And along the 
same lines, how does Atlassian slash ... What  

1020
01:30:25,440 --> 01:30:31,760
have you learned about how to protect this, Pixar 
people call it an ugly baby? When an idea is new  

1021
01:30:31,760 --> 01:30:36,680
they call this an ugly baby. People don't want 
it. It's just like, "Get rid of this thing." 

1022
01:30:36,680 --> 01:30:41,840
Man, that sounds mean to say, but that's the way 
they talk about it. That's the term in creativity.

1023
01:30:44,120 --> 01:30:45,160
That's a good one.

1024
01:30:46,040 --> 01:30:49,360
How do you protect that because that's the biggest 
challenge I think a lot of companies have is just  

1025
01:30:49,360 --> 01:30:53,400
like, "It's been six months. No one wants this. 
We're going to kill it." How do you protect it?  

1026
01:30:53,400 --> 01:30:58,240
So how long did it take for it to show success 
and what have you learned about how to protect?

1027
01:30:58,240 --> 01:31:05,920
Yeah. So basically, internal comms is everything 
there. The way I saw my job as, a large part as  

1028
01:31:05,920 --> 01:31:10,320
being very clear on where we were, on what we were 
learning on, how fast we were learning, how fast  

1029
01:31:10,320 --> 01:31:15,480
we were moving. Being super honest every step of 
the way, not try to make shit up and try to make  

1030
01:31:15,480 --> 01:31:20,720
it bigger than it is, more successful than it is.
On the contrary, be very clear about what we're  

1031
01:31:20,720 --> 01:31:27,360
testing, where we're testing it. Doing that with 
data, doing that with personal customer stories  

1032
01:31:27,360 --> 01:31:33,880
because we all can constantly relate to the 
heart and to the mind. So that's what I always  

1033
01:31:33,880 --> 01:31:39,280
try to weave into comms that I then send weekly.
So we've got this product internally called Atlas,  

1034
01:31:39,280 --> 01:31:43,360
which have a project on Atlas. People can 
subscribe to this project and then weekly  

1035
01:31:43,360 --> 01:31:47,560
you send a tweet-sized update about 
your project. I was using that as a  

1036
01:31:47,560 --> 01:31:52,120
platform to communicate internally about this 
product and there were actually hundreds of  

1037
01:31:52,120 --> 01:31:57,000
people who ended up subscribing to this thing.
Every week when we were at the stage where we  

1038
01:31:57,000 --> 01:32:01,560
were trying to get the first version out 
to customers it was a weekly demo of the  

1039
01:32:01,560 --> 01:32:06,320
product and everything that we built. Show the 
momentum as much as possible. I was even saving  

1040
01:32:06,320 --> 01:32:10,720
features for one week to the next just to ... 
When I knew we were going to be on vacation,  

1041
01:32:10,720 --> 01:32:15,120
for example, just to have something to 
show this train that keeps moving, it keeps  

1042
01:32:15,120 --> 01:32:20,920
moving. You don't want to get in front of it.
But then what I needed to do is to balance that  

1043
01:32:20,920 --> 01:32:25,240
out with all the customer side of things. So when 
we started to put it in front of customers then  

1044
01:32:25,240 --> 01:32:29,720
it was snippets from customer conversations. 
No one is going to read a research report that  

1045
01:32:29,720 --> 01:32:34,040
takes 30 minutes to read. Everyone is happy 
to watch a three-minute snippet with four  

1046
01:32:34,040 --> 01:32:38,960
customers talking about something. So I was 
using that a lot every week by posting those  

1047
01:32:38,960 --> 01:32:42,920
out there and then sharing them widely on Slack 
to go, "This is what we learned. This is what  

1048
01:32:42,920 --> 01:32:46,560
this customer is facing in terms of problem 
with Jira. This is how we're solving it. This  

1049
01:32:46,560 --> 01:32:52,080
is them talking about it," that kind of stuff.
So I was publishing that there and then sending  

1050
01:32:52,080 --> 01:32:58,040
that everywhere on Slack. Those kinds of things 
are what give people a sense of velocity and  

1051
01:32:58,040 --> 01:33:04,760
speed, and no one wants to fuck with a high-speed 
train. You don't get in front of it. That doesn't  

1052
01:33:04,760 --> 01:33:09,960
help and you're going to look bad by doing 
that. So basically that ended up buying us  

1053
01:33:09,960 --> 01:33:14,620
the time that we needed to get out of this, I 
don't know how you call it, the ugly baby phase.

1054
01:33:14,620 --> 01:33:16,560
An ugly baby phase.

1055
01:33:16,560 --> 01:33:20,960
So basically it helped us get out of this 
phase where we don't have anything to show  

1056
01:33:20,960 --> 01:33:25,800
for yet because what we're showing is based on the 
learnings we're trying to get and we're trying to  

1057
01:33:25,800 --> 01:33:32,320
do that with, "Here's some numbers, here's some 
demos, here's some user snippets." Doing that  

1058
01:33:32,320 --> 01:33:38,560
every week because people can consume bite-sized 
content every week. They just struggle with the  

1059
01:33:38,560 --> 01:33:42,920
stuff where you come in three, four months later 
and go, "This is what we have to show for."

1060
01:33:42,920 --> 01:33:46,600
Right. How long was that period before 
it got out of this ugly baby phase for  

1061
01:33:46,600 --> 01:33:49,280
you? When did people start to get 
like, "Oh wow, this might work"?

1062
01:33:49,280 --> 01:33:55,400
Honestly, we had something dogfooding within 
